MongoDB relationships link documents using two main patterns: Embedding (storing related data in one document, good for one-to-one/many) and Referencing (storing IDs to link separate documents, good for many-to-many), offering flexibility for one-to-one, one-to-many, and many-to-many connections, unlike SQL joins, using techniques like embedding or referencing with $lookup for complex queries. 
Embedding (Denormalization)
What it is: Storing related data (e.g., comments in a post, address in a user) directly within the parent document.
Best For: One-to-one and one-to-many relationships where related data is frequently accessed together and doesn't grow excessively (e.g., an author within a book).
Pros: Fast reads (single document fetch), data locality, self-contained.
Cons: Data duplication, potential document size limits. 
Referencing (Normalization)
What it is: Storing unique identifiers (ObjectIDs) of related documents in another document, similar to foreign keys in SQL.
Best For: Many-to-many (e.g., students & courses) and one-to-many where related data is large or independent.
Pros: Reduces data redundancy, better data integrity, flexible for complex relationships.
Cons: Requires multiple queries or $lookup (aggregation) for joins, potentially slower reads. 
Types of Relationships
One-to-One: User and Profile (Embedded or Referenced).
One-to-Many: Author and Books (Embed or Reference book IDs).
Many-to-Many: Students and Courses (Reference Course IDs in Student doc & Student IDs in Course doc). 
Key MongoDB Tools for Relationships
$lookup: The aggregation pipeline stage for performing joins between collections, crucial for complex referencing.
ObjectIDs: Used as references to link documents across collections. 
The choice between embedding and referencing depends on your application's access patterns, data growth, and performance needs, balancing read speed (embedding) with data consistency (referencing).